         <h2 class="alpha">Research Interests</h2>
         <p class="narrow">Topics of interest include: <i>f</i>-Harmonic Maps, namely critical points of the energy 
         functional $E_f(u):=\frac{1}{2} \int_M f |\nabla u|^2 dM$; the associated <i>L&sup2;</i> flow, which
         is called the <i>f</i>-Harmonic Heat Flow; Bi-harmonic Maps which may be defined to be
         critical points of either $E_e(u):=\frac{1}{2} \int_M |\Delta u|^2 dM$ or
         $E_i(u):=\frac{1}{2} \int_M |\tau u|^2 dM$, and the associated flows.</p>
      
      
         <a name="articles">
         <h2 class="alpha">Articles</h2></a>
         <dl style="margin-bottom:40px;">
            <dt><i>f</i>-Harmonic Maps</dt>
            <dd>A study of <i>f</i>-harmonic maps and <i>f</i>-harmonic heat flow. Topics considered include; the class of <i>f</i>-harmonic maps which map the boundary to one point; and locations of singularities under the flow. (<a href="thesis.html" class="alpha">Full Abstract</a>)<br><span class="cite">PhD Thesis, University of Warwick, Coventry, CV4 7AL, UK,
             2004.</span><br>
            (<a href="http://www.neilcourse.co.uk/thesis/Neil_Course_f-harmonic_maps.pdf"
            class="file">Neil_Course_f-harmonic_maps.pdf</a> <font size="-2">935 kB</font>).</dd><p>


            <dt><i>f</i>-harmonic maps which map the boundary of the domain to one point in the target</dt>
            <dd> One considers the class of maps <i>u</i>, from the 2-disc to the 2-sphere, which map the
            boundary of <i>D</i> to one point in <i>S<sup><small>2</small></sup></i>. If <i>u</i> were
            also harmonic, then it is known that <i>u</i> must be constant. However, if <i>u</i> is instead
            <i>f</i>-harmonic then this need not be true. We see
            that there exist functions <i>f: D &rarr; (0,&infin;)</i> and nonconstant <i>f</i>-harmonic maps
            <i>u: D &rarr; S<sup><small>2</small></sup></i> which map the boundary to one point. We also see
            that there exist nonconstant <i>f</i> for which, there is no nonconstant <i>f</i>-harmonic map in
            this class. Finally, we see that there exists a nonconstant <i>f</i>-harmonic map from the torus
            to the 2-sphere.<br><span class="cite">New York J. Math. 13 (2007) 423-435. </span> (<a
            href="http://nyjm.albany.edu/j/2007/13-18.html" class="file">link</a>).</dd>

         </dl>
         
